<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>
<p>
Let \(\{V_i\}_{i=1}^n\) be a finite set of vector spaces.
</p>
<p>
The <b>Cartesian product</b> of these spaces is
\[\prod_{i=1}^nV_i := \{(v_1,\dots, v_n):v_i\in V_i\}.\]
</p>
<p>
This forms a <a knowl="defs/vec/space">vector space</a>.
<details>
<summary>
[explanation]
</summary>
Define an addition of elements componentwise:
\[(v_1,\dots, v_n) + (w_1,\dots, w_n)
:= (v_1 + w_1,\dots, v_n + w_n).\]
Similarly, define componentwise scalar multiplication:
\[\lambda(v_1,\dots, v_n) := (\lambda v_1,\dots,\lambda v_n)\]
We now check the axioms.
<ol>
<li>
Addition is associative:
\[
\begin{align*}
(a_1,\dots,a_n) + ((b_1,\dots,b_n) + (c_1,\dots,c_n))
&= (a_1 + (b_1 + c_1),\dots,a_n + (b_n + c_n))\\
&= ((a_1 + b_1) + c_1,\dots,(a_n + b_n) + c_n)\\
&= ((a_1,\dots, a_n) + (b_1,\dots,b_n)) + (c_1,\dots,c_n)
\end{align*}
\]
</li>
<li>
There is an additive identity:
\[(a_1,\dots,a_n) + (0,\dots,0)
= (a_1 + 0,\dots, a_n + 0) = (a_1,\dots,a_n)\]
\[(0,\dots,0) + (a_1,\dots,a_n)
= (0 + a_1,\dots, 0 + a_n) = (a_1,\dots,a_n)\]
</li>
<li>
Additive inverses exist:
\[(a_1,\dots,a_n) + (-a_1,\dots,-a_n) = (0,\dots,0)\]
</li>
<li>
Addition is commutative:
\[
\begin{align*}
(a_1,\dots,a_n) + (b_1,\dots,b_n) &= (a_1 + b_1,\dots,a_n + b_n)\\
&= (b_1 + a_1,\dots,b_n + a_n)\\
&= (b_1,\dots,b_n) + (a_1,\dots,a_n).
\end{align*}
\]
</li>
<li>
Scalar identity:
\[1(a_1,\dots,a_n) = (1a_1,\dots,1a_n)
= (a_1,\dots,a_n).\]
</li>
<li>
Compatibility with scalar multiplication:
\[
\begin{align*}
\alpha(\beta(x_1,\dots,x_n)) &= \alpha(\beta x_1,\dots,\beta x_n)\\
&= (\alpha(\beta x_1),\dots,\alpha(\beta x_n))\\
&= ((\alpha\beta)x_1,\dots,(\alpha\beta)x_n)\\
&= (\alpha\beta)(x_1,\dots,x_n).
\end{align*}
\]
</li>
<li>
Distributive law:
\[
\begin{align*}
\alpha((x_1,\dots,x_n) + (y_1,\dots,y_n))
&= (\alpha(x_1 + y_1),\dots,\alpha(x_n + y_n))\\
&= (\alpha x_1 + \alpha y_1,\dots,\alpha x_n + \alpha y_n)\\
&= (\alpha x_1,\dots,\alpha x_n) + (\alpha y_1,\dots,\alpha y_n)\\
&= \alpha(x_1,\dots,x_n) + \alpha(y_1,\dots, y_n),\\[1em]
(\alpha + \beta)(x_1,\dots,x_n)
&= ((\alpha + \beta)x_1,\dots,(\alpha + \beta)x_n)\\
&= (\alpha x_1 + \beta x_1, \dots,\alpha x_n + \beta x_n)\\
&= (\alpha x_1,\dots,\alpha x_n) + (\beta x_1,\dots,\beta x_n)\\
&= \alpha(x_1,\dots,x_n) + \beta(x_1,\dots,x_n).
\end{align*}
\]
</li>
</ol>
</details>
</p>
<p>
Furthermore if there exists a vector space
\(W\) such that \(V_i\subseteq W\)
for each \(V_i\),
then there is an isomorphism
\[\Phi:\prod_{i=1}^nV_i\to\bigoplus_{i=1}^nV_i\]
given by
\[(v_1,\dots,v_n)\mapsto v_1 + \cdots + v_n.\]
</p>
</body>
</html>
